A witness presented by the Peoples Democratic Party (PDP) National Assembly candidate in the November 16, 2019, election in Kogi State, Sen. Dino Melaye, Pastor Femi Obalemo, has said he is not an expert in electoral matters. Obalemo, also an accountant, yesterday, told the Kogi State National Assembly Election Petitioner Tribunal sitting in Abuja, that he visited 50 polling units during the election. Earlier in the week, the petitioner, Melaye, told the tribunal that he visited 564 polling units. According to Electoral Laws, candidates and their agents are not allowed to move around from one polling units to the other. In his evidence, he said he was one of those who inspected the Independent National Electoral Commission (INEC) materials used for the election as ordered by the tribunal. When asked about the signatories of the documents he claimed to have inspected, he said he was not one of those who signed it because he was not in the country. He said the evidence he gave as regards other polling agents were relayed to him by other agents who were on ground during the election. When asked if he knows that election can be declared inconclusive, if there is no result, he said, ‘’I don’t have enough information to agree or disagree’’. After the witness was discharged, the petitioner closed his case. The tribunal adjourned the case to April 28, 2020. The electoral umpire, INEC, is expected to open its case on the next adjourned date. Earlier in the week, the tribunal disqualified a witness, Mr Mark John, from testifying before the tribunal.  